3	//! minix.rs SCHED (scheduler) server.
4	//!
5	//! The user-space scheduler (slice 4.3). minix.rs keeps a priority-banded run
6	//! queue in the kernel but makes it *delegatable*: a proc whose
7	//! `Proc::scheduler` names SCHED is handed to SCHED on quantum exhaustion. The
8	//! kernel sends `SCHEDULING_NO_QUANTUM` (`m_source` = the preempted proc) and
9	//! leaves the proc off the run queue; SCHED runs its policy and re-admits the
10	//! proc via `SYS_SCHEDULE`. This mirrors MINIX 3's distinctive design while
11	//! keeping the proven kernel run queue as the kernel-scheduled fallback.
12	//!
13	//! Requests handled:
14	//! - `SCHEDULING_NO_QUANTUM` (kernel → SCHED): re-admit the preempted proc.
15	//! - `SCHEDULING_START` / `SCHEDULING_STOP` / `SCHEDULING_SET_NICE` (PM/RS →
16	//!   SCHED): claim / release / renice a managed proc. Implemented here for PM/RS
17	//!   to drive from slice 4.5+; in 4.3 the kernel pre-delegates a busy stub
18	//!   directly, so only the `NO_QUANTUM` round-trip is exercised live.
19	//!
20	//! Built as a freestanding aarch64 ELF (`servers/sched/user.ld`), packed into
21	//! the boot-image archive by `kernel/build.rs`, and loaded into its own
22	//! per-process AddrSpace at boot. Like every server it drives its loop through
23	//! the SEF framework ([`minixrs_server_rt`]); the policy lives in [`policy`],
24	//! whose pure logic carries the host unit tests.
